# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: c-cpp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:c-cpp/basic-string] The class template `basic_string` stores and manipulates sequences of character-like objects, which are non-array objects of TrivialType and StandardLayoutType.
[src:c-cpp/basic-string] The class is dependent neither on the character type nor on the nature of operations on that type.
[src:c-cpp/basic-string] The definitions of the operations are supplied via the `Traits` template parameter - a specialization of std::char_traits or a compatible traits class.
[src:c-cpp/basic-string] `std::basic_string` satisfies the requirements of AllocatorAwareContainer (except that customized `construct`/`destroy` are not used for construction/destruction of elements), SequenceContainer and ContiguousContainer(since C++17).
[src:c-cpp/basic-string] If any of `Traits::char_type` and `Allocator::char_type` is different from `CharT`, the program is ill-formed.
[src:c-cpp/basic-string] The following behavior-changing defect reports were applied retroactively to previously published C++ standards.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] is a sequence container that encapsulates dynamic size arrays.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] The elements are stored contiguously, which means that elements can be accessed not only through iterators, but also using offsets to regular pointers to elements.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] This means that a pointer to an element of a vector may be passed to any function that expects a pointer to an element of an array.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] The storage of the vector is handled automatically, being expanded as needed.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] Vectors usually occupy more space than static arrays, because more memory is allocated to handle future growth.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] This way a vector does not need to reallocate each time an element is inserted, but only when the additional memory is exhausted.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] The total amount of allocated memory can be queried using capacity() function.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] Extra memory can be returned to the system via a call to shrink_to_fit().
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] Reallocations are usually costly operations in terms of performance.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] The reserve() function can be used to eliminate reallocations if the number of elements is known beforehand.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] `std::vector` (for `T` other than `bool`) meets the requirements of Container, AllocatorAwareContainer(since C++11), SequenceContainer, ContiguousContainer(since C++17) and ReversibleContainer.
[src:c-cpp/container-vector] The standard library provides a specialization of `std::vector` for the type `bool`, which may be optimized for space efficiency.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] may be a null pointer, however the return value (number of bytes that would be written not including the null terminator) is still calculated and returned.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] The **format** string consists of ordinary byte characters (except `**%**`), which are copied unchanged into the output stream, and conversion specifications.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Converts a **signed integer** into decimal representation *[-]dddd*.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Converts an **unsigned integer** into binary representation *bbbb*.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Converts an **unsigned integer** into octal representation *oooo*.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Converts an **unsigned integer** into hexadecimal representation *hhhh*.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Converts an **unsigned integer** into decimal representation *dddd*.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Converts **floating-point number** to the decimal notation in the style *[-]ddd.ddd*.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Converts **floating-point number** to the decimal exponent notation.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Converts **floating-point number** to the hexadecimal exponent notation.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Converts **floating-point number** to decimal or decimal exponent notation depending on the value and the *precision*.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Returns the **number of characters written** so far by this call to the function.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Writes an implementation defined character sequence defining a **pointer**.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] The floating-point conversion functions convert infinity to `inf` or `infinity`.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Which one is used is implementation defined.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] Not-a-number is converted to `nan` or `nan(*char_sequence*)`.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] The conversion specifier used to print `char`, `unsigned char`, `signed char`, `short`, and `unsigned short` expects promoted types of default argument promotions, but before printing its value will be converted to `char`, `unsigned char`, `signed char`, `short`, and `unsigned short`.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] It is safe to pass values of these types because of the promotion that takes place when a variadic function is called.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] The correct conversion specifications for the fixed-width character types (int8_t, etc) are defined in the header <inttypes.h> (although PRIdMAX, PRIuMAX, etc is synonymous with `%jd`, `%ju`, etc).
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] The memory-writing conversion specifier `%n` is a common target of security exploits where format strings depend on user input and is not supported by the bounds-checked `printf_s` family of functions(since C11).
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] There is a sequence point after the action of each conversion specifier; this permits storing multiple `%n` results in the same variable or, as an edge case, printing a string modified by an earlier `%n` within the same call.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] If a conversion specification is invalid, the behavior is undefined.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] number of characters transmitted to the output stream or negative value if an output error or an encoding error (for string and character conversion specifiers) occurred.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] (not counting the terminating null character), or a negative value if an encoding error (for string and character conversion specifiers) occurred.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] was ignored, or a negative value if an encoding error (for string and character conversion specifiers) occurred.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] number of characters transmitted to the output stream or negative value if an output error, a runtime constraints violation error, or an encoding error occurred.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] ), or zero on runtime constraint violations, and negative value on encoding errors.
[src:c-cpp/io-fprintf] was ignored, or a negative value if a runtime constraints violation or an encoding error occurred.
[src:c-cpp/language-classes] A class type is defined by class-specifier, which appears in decl-specifier-seq of the declaration syntax.
[src:c-cpp/language-classes] See class declaration for the syntax of the class specifier.
[src:c-cpp/language-classes] class templates or function templates) may appear in the body of any non-local class/struct/union.
[src:c-cpp/language-classes] However, a non-static data member may use the name `T` as long as there are no user-declared constructors.
[src:c-cpp/language-classes] A class with at least one declared or inherited virtual member function is *polymorphic*.
[src:c-cpp/language-classes] Objects of this type are polymorphic objects and have runtime type information stored as part of the object representation, which may be queried with `dynamic_cast` and `typeid`.
[src:c-cpp/language-classes] Virtual member functions participate in dynamic binding.
[src:c-cpp/language-classes] A class with at least one declared or inherited pure virtual member function is an abstract class.
[src:c-cpp/language-classes] Notes: the implicit-lifetime property is clarified by defect report P0593R6.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] Constructs a closure (an unnamed function object capable of capturing variables in scope).
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The lambda expression with a parameter list.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The lambda expression without a parameter list.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] A variable `__func__` is implicitly defined at the beginning of body, with semantics as described here.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The lambda expression is a prvalue expression of unique unnamed non-union non-aggregate class type, known as *closure type*, which is declared (for the purposes of ADL) in the smallest block scope, class scope, or namespace scope that contains the lambda expression.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] Executes the body of the lambda expression, when invoked.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] When accessing a variable, accesses its captured copy (for the entities captured by copy), or the original object (for the entities captured by reference).
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The parameter list of `operator()` is params if it is provided, otherwise the parameter list is empty.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The return type of `operator()` is the type specified in trailing ﻿.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] If trailing is not provided, the return type of `operator()` is automatically deduced.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] Unless the keyword `mutable` was used in the lambda specifiers, or an explicit object parameter is present(since C++23), the cv-qualifier of `operator()` is `const` and the objects that were captured by copy are non-modifiable from inside this `operator()`.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] Explicit `const` qualifier is not allowed.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] `operator()` is never virtual and cannot have the `volatile` qualifier.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The exception specification except on the lambda expression applies to `operator()`.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] For the purpose of name lookup, determining the type and value of the `this` pointer and for accessing non-static class members, the body of the closure type's `operator()` is considered in the context of the lambda expression.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] If a non-reference entity is captured by reference, implicitly or explicitly, and `operator()` of the closure object is invoked after the entity's lifetime has ended, undefined behavior occurs.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The C++ closures do not extend the lifetimes of objects captured by reference.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] Same applies to the lifetime of the current `*this` object captured via `**this**`.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] This user-defined conversion function is only defined if the lambda expression has no captures ﻿ and has no explicit object parameter(since C++23).
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] It is a public, constexpr,(since C++17) non-virtual, non-explicit, const noexcept member function of the closure object.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The copy constructor and the move constructor are declared as defaulted and may be implicitly-defined according to the usual rules for copy constructors and move constructors.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] If the lambda expression captures anything by copy (either implicitly with capture clause `**[=]**` or explicitly with a capture that does not include the character &, e.g.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] `**[a, b, c]**`), the closure type includes unnamed non-static data members, declared in unspecified order, that hold copies of all entities that were so captured.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] Those data members that correspond to captures without initializers are direct-initialized when the lambda expression is evaluated.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] Those that correspond to captures with initializers are initialized as the initializer requires (could be copy- or direct-initialization).
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] If an array is captured, array elements are direct-initialized in increasing index order.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The order in which the data members are initialized is the order in which they are declared (which is unspecified).
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The type of each data member is the type of the corresponding captured entity, except if the entity has reference type (in that case, references to functions are captured as lvalue references to the referenced functions, and references to objects are captured as copies of the referenced objects).
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] For the entities that are captured by reference (with the capture-default `**[&]**` or when using the character &, e.g.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] `**[&a, &b, &c]**`), it is unspecified if additional data members are declared in the closure type, but any such additional members must satisfy LiteralType(since C++17).
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The captures defines the outside variables that are accessible from within the lambda function body.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] If the capture-default is `**&**`, subsequent simple captures must not begin with `**&**`.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The current object (`*this`) can be implicitly captured if either capture default is present.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] If implicitly captured, it is always captured by reference, even if the capture default is `**=**`.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] For such lambda expression, the *reaching scope* is defined as the set of enclosing scopes up to and including the innermost enclosing function (and its parameters).
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] This includes nested block scopes and the scopes of enclosing lambdas if this lambda is nested.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The identifier in any capture without an initializer (other than the `this`-capture) is looked up using usual unqualified name lookup in the *reaching scope* of the lambda.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] The result of the lookup must be a variable with automatic storage duration declared in the reaching scope, or a structured binding whose corresponding variable satisfies such requirements(since C++20).
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] For the purpose of determining implicit captures, `typeid` is never considered to make its operands unevaluated.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] If the body of a lambda odr-uses an entity captured by copy, the member of the closure type is accessed.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] Any entity captured by a lambda (implicitly or explicitly) is odr-used by the lambda expression (therefore, implicit capture by a nested lambda triggers implicit capture in the enclosing lambda).
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] All implicitly-captured variables must be declared within the *reaching scope* of the lambda.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] If a lambda expression (or a specialization of a generic lambda's function call operator)(since C++14) ODR-uses `*this` or any variable with automatic storage duration, it must be captured by the lambda expression.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] Members of anonymous unions members cannot be captured.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] Bit-fields can only be captured by copy.
[src:c-cpp/language-lambda] This example shows how to pass a lambda to a generic algorithm and how objects resulting from a lambda expression can be stored in std::function objects.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Declares a variable of a pointer or pointer-to-member type.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] There are no pointers to references and there are no pointers to bit-fields.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Typically, mentions of "pointers" without elaboration do not include pointers to (non-static) members.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] A pointer that points to an object *represents the address* of the first byte in memory occupied by the object.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] A pointer past the end of an object *represents the address* of the first byte in memory after the end of the storage occupied by the object.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Note that two pointers that represent the same address may nonetheless have different values.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Indirection through an invalid pointer value and passing an invalid pointer value to a deallocation function have undefined behavior.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Any other use of an invalid pointer value has implementation-defined behavior.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Some implementations might define that copying an invalid pointer value causes a system-generated runtime fault.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Pointers to class objects may also appear as the left-hand operands of the member access operators `operator->` and `operator->*`.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] If `Derived` is polymorphic, such a pointer may be used to make virtual function calls.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Certain addition, subtraction, increment, and decrement operators are defined for pointers to elements of arrays: such pointers satisfy the LegacyRandomAccessIterator requirements and allow the C++ library algorithms to work with raw arrays.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Many implementations also provide strict total ordering of pointers of random origin, e.g. if they are implemented as addresses within continuous virtual address space.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] This makes it possible to use all pointers of random origin as keys in standard associative containers such as std::set or std::map.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Pointer to object of any type can be implicitly converted to pointer to (possibly cv-qualified) `void`; the pointer value is unchanged.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] If the original pointer is pointing to a base class subobject within an object of some polymorphic type, `dynamic_cast` may be used to obtain a `void*` that is pointing at the complete object of the most derived type.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Pointers to `void` have the same size, representation and alignment as pointers to `char`.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Pointers to `void` are used to pass objects of unknown type, which is common in C interfaces: std::malloc returns `void*`, std::qsort expects a user-provided callback that accepts two `const void*` arguments.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] `pthread_create` expects a user-provided callback that accepts and returns `void*`.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] In all cases, it is the caller's responsibility to cast the pointer to the correct type before use.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] A pointer to function can be initialized with an address of a non-member function or a static member function.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Unlike functions or references to functions, pointers to functions are objects and thus can be stored in arrays, copied, assigned, etc.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Equality comparison operators are defined for pointers to functions (they compare equal if pointing to the same function).
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] A pointer to non-static member object `m` which is a member of class `C` can be initialized with the expression `&C::m` exactly.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Expressions such as `&(C::m)` or `&m` inside `C`'s member function do not form pointers to members.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] The pointed-to type of a pointer-to-member may be a pointer-to-member itself: pointers to members can be multilevel, and can be cv-qualified differently at every level.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] A pointer to non-static member function `f` which is a member of class `C` can be initialized with the expression `&C::f` exactly.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Expressions such as `&(C::f)` or `&f` inside `C`'s member function do not form pointers to member functions.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Such a pointer may be used as the right-hand operand of the pointer-to-member access operators `operator.*` and `operator->*`.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Pointers of every type have a special value known as *null pointer value* of that type.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] A pointer whose value is null does not point to an object or a function (the behavior of dereferencing a null pointer is undefined), and compares equal to all pointers of the same type whose value is also *null*.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] The macro NULL can also be used, it expands to an implementation-defined null pointer constant.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Zero-initialization and value-initialization also initialize pointers to their null values.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] Null pointers can be used to indicate the absence of an object (e.g. std::function::target()), or as other error condition indicators (e.g. dynamic_cast).
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] In general, a function that receives a pointer argument almost always needs to check if the value is null and handle that case differently (for example, the delete expression does nothing when a null pointer is passed).
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] In general, implicit conversion from one multi-level pointer to another follows the rules described in qualification conversions.
[src:c-cpp/language-pointer] When an operand of a comparison operator or any of the second and third operands of a conditional operator is a pointer or pointer-to-member, a composite pointer type is determined to be the common type of these operands.
[src:c-cpp/language-reference] Declares a named variable as a reference, that is, an alias to an already-existing object or function.
[src:c-cpp/language-reference] A reference is required to be initialized to refer to a valid object or function: see reference initialization.
[src:c-cpp/language-reference] The type “reference to (possibly cv-qualified) `void`” cannot be formed.
[src:c-cpp/language-reference] Reference types cannot be cv-qualified at the top level; there is no syntax for that in declaration, and if a qualification is added to a typedef-name or `decltype` specifier,(since C++11) or type template parameter, it is ignored.
[src:c-cpp/language-reference] Although references always refer to valid objects or functions upon initialization, it is possible to create a program where the lifetime of the referred-to object ends, but the reference remains accessible (*dangling*).
[src:c-cpp/language-reference] Note that rvalue references and lvalue references to const extend the lifetimes of temporary objects (see Reference initialization for rules and exceptions).
[src:c-cpp/language-reference] If the referred-to object was destroyed (e.g. by explicit destructor call), but the storage was not deallocated, a reference to the out-of-lifetime object may be used in limited ways, and may become valid if the object is recreated in the same storage (see Access outside of lifetime for details).
[src:c-cpp/memory-malloc] Allocates `size` bytes of uninitialized storage.
[src:c-cpp/memory-malloc] If allocation succeeds, returns a pointer that is suitably aligned for any object type with fundamental alignment.
[src:c-cpp/memory-malloc] If `size` is zero, the behavior of `malloc` is implementation-defined.
[src:c-cpp/memory-malloc] For example, a null pointer may be returned.
[src:c-cpp/memory-malloc] Alternatively, a non-null pointer may be returned; but such a pointer should not be dereferenced, and should be passed to free to avoid memory leaks.
[src:c-cpp/memory-malloc] On success, returns the pointer to the beginning of newly allocated memory.
[src:c-cpp/memory-malloc] To avoid a memory leak, the returned pointer must be deallocated with free() or realloc().
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] `std::shared_ptr` is a smart pointer that retains shared ownership of an object through a pointer.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] Several `shared_ptr` objects may own the same object.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] The object is destroyed using delete-expression or a custom deleter that is supplied to `shared_ptr` during construction.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] A `shared_ptr` can share ownership of an object while storing a pointer to another object.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] This feature can be used to point to member objects while owning the object they belong to.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] The stored pointer is the one accessed by get(), the dereference and the comparison operators.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] The managed pointer is the one passed to the deleter when use count reaches zero.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] A `shared_ptr` may also own no objects, in which case it is called *empty* (an empty `shared_ptr` may have a non-null stored pointer if the aliasing constructor was used to create it).
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] All specializations of `shared_ptr` meet the requirements of CopyConstructible, CopyAssignable, and LessThanComparable and are contextually convertible to `bool`.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] All member functions (including copy constructor and copy assignment) can be called by multiple threads on different `shared_ptr` objects without additional synchronization even if these objects are copies and share ownership of the same object.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] If multiple threads of execution access the same `shared_ptr` object without synchronization and any of those accesses uses a non-const member function of `shared_ptr` then a data race will occur; the std::atomic<shared_ptr> can be used to prevent the data race.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] When `shared_ptr` is created by calling std::make_shared or std::allocate_shared, the memory for both the control block and the managed object is created with a single allocation.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] The managed object is constructed in-place in a data member of the control block.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] When `shared_ptr` is created via one of the `shared_ptr` constructors, the managed object and the control block must be allocated separately.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] In this case, the control block stores a pointer to the managed object.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] The pointer held by the `shared_ptr` directly is the one returned by get(), while the pointer/object held by the control block is the one that will be deleted when the number of shared owners reaches zero.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] These pointers are not necessarily equal.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] The destructor of `shared_ptr` decrements the number of shared owners of the control block.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] If that counter reaches zero, the control block calls the destructor of the managed object.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] The control block does not deallocate itself until the std::weak_ptr counter reaches zero as well.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] In existing implementations, the number of weak pointers is incremented ([1], [2]) if there is a shared pointer to the same control block.
[src:c-cpp/memory-shared-ptr] To satisfy thread safety requirements, the reference counters are typically incremented using an equivalent of std::atomic::fetch_add with std::memory_order_relaxed (decrementing requires stronger ordering to safely destroy the control block).
[src:c-cpp/memory-unique-ptr] `std::unique_ptr` is a smart pointer that owns (is responsible for) and manages another object via a pointer and subsequently disposes of that object when the `unique_ptr` goes out of scope.
[src:c-cpp/memory-unique-ptr] The object is disposed of, using a potentially user-supplied deleter, by calling `get_deleter()(ptr)`.
[src:c-cpp/memory-unique-ptr] The default deleter (`std::default_delete`) uses the `delete` operator, which destroys the object and deallocates the memory.
[src:c-cpp/memory-unique-ptr] A `unique_ptr` may alternatively own no object, in which case it is described as *empty*.
[src:c-cpp/memory-unique-ptr] Manages a dynamically-allocated array of objects (e.g., allocated with `new[]`).
[src:c-cpp/memory-unique-ptr] The class satisfies the requirements of MoveConstructible and MoveAssignable, but of neither CopyConstructible nor CopyAssignable.
[src:c-cpp/memory-unique-ptr] If `T*` was not a valid type (e.g., `T` is a reference type), a program that instantiates the definition of `std::unique_ptr<T, Deleter>` is ill-formed.
